 <br>
** Im going to refer to MM alot in this lil guide of mine. This is in NO WAY picking on anyone, only using some points as an example for all to comprehend **<br>
<br>
 #1- NEVER EVER NEVER sit and med at a dungeon zone line. Unless you enjoy torturing yourself, or plan to delete the character anyway, sitting at a zone line and going AFK while you med is unwise, to be polite.<br>
 #2- Dungeons AINT safe. If they were safe, or like any other outdoor zone, the exp bonus wouldnt be there. Danger is EVERYWHERE so pay attention.<br>
 #3- DONT wander off. Yes, some of the guild members may seem like gods to some of you considering their levels, weapons, pets, spells, armor...but we will ALL drop like flies if someone pulls a nasty train on us (like MM =\)<br>
Wandering from the huddle can result in mass death to the guildmembers.<br>
 #4- PAY ATTENTION. It never ceases to amaze me how relatively unaware some people can be. &quot;Hmmm...Im sitting in the middle of one of the WORST preKunark dungeons ever designed, everything cons red to me, and the guild is constantly pulling 6-7 Mobs at a time. Hmmm..think Ill go get that soda now, or give Vicki a call and ask her how her date went with Alan...&quot; <br>
 #5- MOVE IT. Sometimes, you gotta move or die.  If you were AFK for the past 10 minutes in a bad place and didnt move when your group did, Im sorry.... YOU killed YOU by NOT paying attention. If u cant stay focused on the raid you have joined, do the group a favor and camp or just dont go. Getting people killed is not fun =\ This hasnt happened to us yet, Im just putting this in here as a warning.<br>
 #6- FOCUS. Even the high levs in a fairly weak dungeon need to concentrate. Meaning, I cant go right, Layha goes left, and UF goes forward. Yes, we may each be powerful enough to kill the mobs nearby, but we can screw up and pull an unseen HORDE in seconds. We need to stick together when we move on raids. A good example of this is when UF died, and he, I, and Ralluin were retrieving his corpse. The three of us, when we were alert and working as one piece of a 3 part machine, REALLY did some damage in a short amount of time.<br>
 #7- ASSIST. This is so old school, my regular readers will prolly skip this section. For the newcomers that accidentally stumble across the board, here it is: ALWAYS, especially in a dungeon when its not uncommon for 4-5 mobs to be pulled at once, ASSIST the puller. Dont do the hero thing and solo your own personal mob. Assist whoever is designated puller. If we get overrun, I always target my puller, and start nuking his target. One by one, they start to die FAST. Three tanks to one mob = DEAD mob. <br>
 #8- PROTECT THE HEALER. This is the only time you should disengage the pullers target. If you dont have a healer, we all die =\<br>
 #9- DONT OVERBURN. Its tempting when we KNOW we got so much firepower that we HAVE to show it off. We know who we are... =p But overnuking a target will kill you as FAST as healing a guildie. MEGA aggro when you let the mob and his friends know just how bad you truly are. You'll be swarmed and consumed before the mob can be killed or taunted off. Good rule of thumb for most offensive castings...wait until the MOB's hp are at 75%, THEN unleash one.<br>
 #10- Dont sweat the loot/exp thing. If we all work together as a TEAM, not as individuals wandering a dungeon's halls aimlessly, we will all have FUN. Which to me and hopefully our small lil guild is more important than xp or loot. We dont hang out together often enough, so lets just enjoy our time together when we DO hang out. Y'know how much xp or PHAT loot I got from all our previous raids? NOTHING!! Not a PIXEL of xp, and nothin but copper or silver that I feed to my pet =p <br>
 #11- HAVE FUN DAMMIT!! Thats an order for all raids =p<br>
<br>
 <br>
Ok, I may have forgot to include a few things, but what Ive written is just a small common sense thing. Some of it is old news for you old timers, but the younger players new to EQ may get something out of this. And it even helps me to read over it as I type it. The more you think about a subject, the more familiar and second nature it becomes to act upon it. Anyway, thus endeth the sermon..cyas in game =)<br>
